{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617143"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16457"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16457"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9148"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75118"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9148"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60626"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7114"},{"type":"tags","id":"10056"},{"type":"tags","id":"10476"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21730"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75118"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECytotoxic oedema is a pathological process where cells swell due to the accumulation of fluid in the intracellular space. This process commonly occurs in conditions such as stroke and traumatic brain injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism responsible for cytotoxic oedema?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased ATP production","Blood-brain barrier disruption","Increased hydrostatic pressure","Decreased plasma oncotic pressure","Lymphatic system dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECytotoxic oedema is a key pathophysiological process that occurs when energy failure leads to cellular swelling. \u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased ATP production\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary initiating event, as it causes failure of energy-dependent ion pumps, particularly the Na+/K+-ATPase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood-brain barrier disruption\u003C/strong\u003E characterises vasogenic oedema, which occurs later in stroke evolution, but is not the primary mechanism of cytotoxic oedema\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased hydrostatic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to oedema formation in conditions like hypertensive emergencies but is not the primary mechanism in cytotoxic oedema\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased plasma oncotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E can cause oedema in conditions like nephrotic syndrome but does not play a significant role in cytotoxic oedema formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphatic system dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E can cause oedema in peripheral tissues but is not relevant to cytotoxic oedema formation in the brain\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sequence of events in cytotoxic oedema begins with energy failure and decreased ATP production, leading to Na+/K+-ATPase pump failure. This results in sodium accumulation within cells, creating an osmotic gradient that draws water into the intracellular compartment, causing cellular swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cytotoxic oedema occurs when cellular energy failure leads to sodium and water accumulation within cells.","ATP depletion causes failure of Na+/K+-ATPase pumps, leading to intracellular sodium accumulation.","The osmotic gradient created by increased intracellular sodium draws water into cells, causing them to swell."],"references":["Michinaga S, Koyama Y. Pathogenesis of brain edema and investigation into anti-edema drugs. Int J Mol Sci. 2015 Apr 30;16(5):9949-75. doi: 10.3390/ijms16059949. PMID: 25941935; PMCID: PMC4463627.","Liang D, Bhatta S, Gerzanich V, Simard JM. Cytotoxic edema: mechanisms of pathological cell swelling. Neurosurg Focus. 2007 May 15;22(5):E2. doi: 10.3171/foc.2007.22.5.3. PMID: 17613233; PMCID: PMC2740913.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60626"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16457"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60626"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T23:03:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T23:06:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9148"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75118"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id